  "text": "The Kubernetes API server authentication chain is implemented in kubernetes/kubernetes v1.32.0. The core chain construction is in pkg/kubeapiserver/authenticator/config.go, specifically in the Config.New() method (lines 100-236), which orchestrates the entire authentication flow.\n\nThe authentication chain includes:\n\n1. **Bearer Token Authenticator** (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/authentication/request/bearertoken/bearertoken.go): Implements the New() function and Authenticator type that extracts and validates bearer tokens from HTTP Authorization headers. The AuthenticateRequest() method (lines 42-76) parses the Authorization header and delegates token validation to underlying token authenticators.\n\n2. **Client Certificate Authenticator** (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/authentication/request/x509/x509.go): Implements X.509 client certificate authentication via the NewDynamic() function, which validates client certificates presented in the TLS connection against configured CA bundles.\n\n3. **Service Account Token Authenticators**: Implemented across three files in pkg/serviceaccount/:\n   - jwt.go: Contains JWTTokenAuthenticator() function (line 227) that creates a generic JWT token authenticator for service account tokens. The jwtTokenAuthenticator type (lines 316-321) implements AuthenticateToken() method (lines 334-412) to verify JWT signatures and validate token claims. PublicKeysGetter interface (lines 247-260) and StaticPublicKeysGetter() function (line 277) provide the mechanism for retrieving public keys to verify signatures.\n   - legacy.go: Implements NewLegacyValidator() function (line 65) and legacyValidator type (lines 79-83) for legacy service account token validation. The Validate() method (lines 87-181) verifies secret-based tokens against the API server's stored copy and tracks token usage for deprecation purposes.\n   - claims.go: Implements NewValidator() function (line 132) and validator type (lines 138-140) for modern service account token validation. The Validate() method (lines 144-292) validates bound tokens (secret, pod, or node-bound), checks service account existence, and enforces token expiration. Claims() function (line 70) generates token claims with optional pod/node binding information.\n\n4. **Anonymous Authenticator** (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/authentication/request/anonymous/anonymous.go): Implements NewAuthenticator() function (line 55) that creates an Authenticator type (lines 32-34). The AuthenticateRequest() method (lines 36-49) authenticates requests as the anonymous user when authentication is enabled.\n\n5. **Chain Combinators**: Two union authenticators combine multiple authenticators:\n   - staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/authentication/request/union/union.go: Combines request-level authenticators (x509, bearer token wrapper, front-proxy) via New() and NewFailOnError() functions.\n   - staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/authentication/token/union/union.go: Combines token-level authenticators (service account tokens, bootstrap tokens, webhook tokens) via New() and NewFailOnError() functions.\n\nThe Config.New() method coordinates the chain construction by (1) creating individual authenticators based on configuration, (2) wrapping token authenticators with audience handling, (3) combining multiple token authenticators using tokenunion.New(), (4) adding optional caching with tokencache.New(), (5) wrapping the combined token authenticators with bearertoken.New() for HTTP Authorization header extraction, (6) combining all request-level authenticators with union.New(), (7) adding authenticated group information with group.NewAuthenticatedGroupAdder(), and (8) optionally appending anonymous.NewAuthenticator() at the end of the chain for permissive anonymous access when configured."
}
